  <span class="tag tds">TDS / TCS</span>
  <h1>TDS under the Income-tax Act, 2025: what changes from 1 April 2026</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span>
    <b>CA SR</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>23 Jun 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>7 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">

  <p class="lead">The Income-tax Act, 2025 comes into force on 1 April 2026. The TDS machinery has not been re-invented — but every section number, return and certificate you quote on the deduction side changes. Here is the practical map for deductors.</p>

  <p>The substantive law — who deducts, at what rate, above which threshold — is carried forward largely unchanged. What changes is the <b>architecture</b>: the scattered 1961-Act sections are consolidated, and the challan, return and certificate forms are renumbered under the Income-tax Rules, 2026. If you deduct tax, your masters, utilities and templates need updating before the first payment on or after 1 April 2026.</p>

  <h2>Three sections now hold everything</h2>
  <p>The old structure spread TDS across sections 192 to 194T and TCS under 206C. The new Act collapses this into three homes:</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>New section</th><th>Covers</th><th>Replaces (1961 Act)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><b>Sec 392</b></td><td>Salary &amp; premature EPF withdrawal</td><td>192 and 192A (EPF under 392(7))</td></tr>
        <tr><td><b>Sec 393</b></td><td>All non-salary TDS — 393(1) residents, 393(2) non-residents</td><td>193, 194, 194A–194T, 195 and the rest</td></tr>
        <tr><td><b>Sec 394</b></td><td>All Tax Collected at Source (TCS)</td><td>206C and its sub-sections</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout note">Premature EPF withdrawal (old 194/192A territory) is a common slip: it sits with <b>salary in Sec 392(7)</b>, <b>not</b> in the non-salary Sec 393. Its payment code is 1004.</div>

  <h2>Quote a payment code, not the old section</h2>
  <p>For any payment where the earlier of <b>credit or payment</b> falls on or after 1 April 2026, you must reference the relevant table item of Section 393 (or 394 for TCS) — expressed as a <b>numeric payment code in the 1001–1067 range</b> — on the challan and statement. The old labels "194C", "194J" and so on must not be quoted for these payments. The challan format, the portal/bank payment process and the payment deadlines are unchanged; only the section reference changes.</p>

  <h2>The forms you file are renumbered</h2>
  <p>Every return and certificate gets a new number. The function is the same — only the form ID changes:</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Purpose</th><th>Old form</th><th>New form</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Salary TDS return (quarterly)</td><td>24Q</td><td><b>138</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Non-salary TDS return (resident)</td><td>26Q</td><td><b>140</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>TDS return — non-residents</td><td>27Q</td><td><b>144</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>TCS return (quarterly)</td><td>27EQ</td><td><b>143</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Challan-cum-statement (property / rent / VDA / 194M)</td><td>26QB/QC/QD/QE</td><td><b>141</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Salary TDS certificate</td><td>Form 16</td><td><b>130</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Non-salary TDS certificate</td><td>Form 16A</td><td><b>131</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>No-deduction declaration</td><td>15G / 15H</td><td><b>121</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Lower-deduction certificate application</td><td>Form 13</td><td><b>128</b></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Foreign remittance</td><td>15CA / 15CB</td><td><b>145 / 146</b></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>The transition rule that matters most</h2>
  <p>The dividing line is the date of the transaction — specifically the <b>earlier of credit or payment</b>:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Earlier event <b>up to 31 March 2026</b> → old Act: quote 194-series sections, file 24Q/26Q/27Q, issue Form 16/16A.</li>
    <li>Earlier event <b>on or after 1 April 2026</b> → new Act: quote Section 393/394 payment codes, file Forms 138/140/143/144.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For FY 2025-26, the Q4 (Jan–Mar 2026) returns continue in the old forms — for example, the Q4 TCS statement is still filed in Form 27EQ.</p>

  <h2>Rates and thresholds: unchanged, but remember Budget 2025</h2>
  <p>The new Act does not reset rates. The thresholds you should already be applying from FY 2025-26 carry forward, including the Budget 2025 rationalisations:</p>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Payment</th><th>Rate</th><th>Threshold (FY 2026-27)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Professional fees (old 194J)</td><td>10%</td><td>₹50,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Commission / brokerage (old 194H)</td><td>2%</td><td>₹20,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Rent — land &amp; building (old 194I)</td><td>10%</td><td>₹50,000 per month</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Bank/post-office interest (old 194A)</td><td>10%</td><td>₹50,000 (₹1,00,000 senior citizen)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Firm/LLP to partners (old 194T)</td><td>10%</td><td>₹20,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Compensation on acquisition (old 194LA)</td><td>10%</td><td>₹5,00,000</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <div class="callout note">Look up any section, rate, threshold and the new form against the old number in the <a href="numberiq-tds-chart-fy2026-27.html">NumberIQ TDS Rate Finder</a> — it carries the full old-to-new mapping with plain-English examples.</div>

  <h2>A short readiness checklist for deductors</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Update accounting/payroll masters to the new payment codes (1001–1067) before the first April 2026 deduction.</li>
    <li>Confirm your return-filing utility / vendor supports Forms 138, 140, 143 and 144.</li>
    <li>Re-label certificate templates: Form 16 → 130, Form 16A → 131.</li>
    <li>Brief AP and treasury that the cut-over is on the <b>earlier of credit or payment</b>, not the invoice date.</li>
    <li>For non-residents, keep using the lower of Act vs DTAA rate with TRC + Form 10F on file; foreign-remittance reporting moves to Forms 145/146.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="callout warn">This note reflects the Income-tax Act, 2025 and the Income-tax Rules, 2026 as reported by leading commentaries and the e-filing portal as on June 2026. Cross-check the final notified Rules and any CBDT circulars before relying on specific form numbers in client filings, and obtain professional sign-off for non-routine transactions.</div>

